{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/gastrointestinal-tract-lower-cancers-recognition-referral/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"6fb80d28-e5bb-508d-a25b-777f1001b8e0","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field fa7172a2-d67b-48ed-b6ec-ee1a46d86dde --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field fa7172a2-d67b-48ed-b6ec-ee1a46d86dde -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 7293acb1-ca3c-401e-9deb-7dbb016a895d --><!-- begin field 261cff17-2846-460a-be29-59932ed21d18 --><ul><li><strong>Colorectal cancer:</strong><ul><li>Around 40,000 new colorectal cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK, up to a quarter of these following screening.</li><li>A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately one person with colorectal cancer every year.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Anal cancer:</strong><ul><li>Just over 1000 new anal cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK, meaning that a full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately 1â€“2 people with anal cancer during their career.</li><li>Anal cancer occurs in both sexes, though nearly two-thirds occur in women.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/gastrointestinal-tract-lower-cancers-recognition-referral/references/\">National Collaborating Centre for Cancer, 2015</a>]</p><!-- end field 261cff17-2846-460a-be29-59932ed21d18 --><!-- end item 7293acb1-ca3c-401e-9deb-7dbb016a895d -->","topic":{"id":"3aca7a59-2727-5c46-8b62-1fc8094a529e","topicId":"f20d0c44-993c-4f12-bae7-c3636eec15ae","topicName":"Gastrointestinal tract (lower) cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"gastrointestinal-tract-lower-cancers-recognition-referral","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2021","chapters":[{"id":"a424c7f1-33fc-59aa-b3d5-28e75f5a141d","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d5343468-d088-5069-a5